{{lowercase|title=ls}}{{Infobox Website |name = eBird |logo = Logo ebird.png |logo_size = 200px |url = [http://ebird.org/content/ebird/ eBird] |type = Wildlife database |author = [[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] |launch date = 2002 |language = [[Bulgarian (language)|Bulgarian]], [[Chinese (language)|Chinese]], [[Croatian (language)|Croatian]], [[Czech (language)|Czech]], [[Danish (language)|Danish]], [[Dutch (language)|Dutch]], [[German (language)|German]], [[English (language)|English]], [[Faroese (language)|Faroese]], [[Finnish (language)|Finnish]], [[French (language)|French]], [[Creole (language)|Creole]], [[Hebrew (language)|Hebrew]], [[Indonesian (language)|Indonesian]], [[Icelandic (language)|Icelandic]], [[Italian (language)|Italian]], [[Japanese (language)|Japanese]], [[Latvian (language)|Latvian]], [[Malayalam (language)|Malayalam]], [[Mongolian (language)|Mongolian]], [[Bokmål|Norwegian (Bokmål)]], [[Polish (language)|Polish]], [[Portuguese (language)|Portuguese]], [[Russian (language)|Russian]], [[Serbian (language)|Serbian]], [[Spanish (language)|Spanish]], [[Swedish (language)|Swedish]], [[Thai (language)|Thai]], [[Turkish (language)|Turkish]], and [[Ukrainian (language)|Ukrainian]] |current status = Active }} '''eBird''' is an online [[database]] of [[bird]] observations providing [[scientists]], researchers and amateur naturalists with real-time data about [[Bird atlas|bird distribution and abundance]]. Originally restricted to sightings from the [[Western Hemisphere]], it was widened to include [[New Zealand]] in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|last=eBird New Zealand|title=About eBird|url=http://ebird.org/content/newzealand/about|publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]]|accessdate=5 June 2010|year=2008|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922005815/http://ebird.org/content/newzealand/about|archivedate=22 September 2010|df=}}</ref> and was widened to cover the whole world in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=eBird|title=Global eBird almost there! -- 3 June update|url=http://ebird.org/content/ebird/news/global-ebird-underway-27-may-update|publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology|accessdate=5 June 2010|year=2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603231152/http://ebird.org/content/ebird/news/global-ebird-underway-27-may-update|archivedate=3 June 2010|df=}}</ref> eBird has been described as an ambitious example of enlisting [[amateurs]] to gather data on [[biodiversity]] for use in science.<ref>[http://www.asis.org/Bulletin/Oct-03/levincragin.html "The Role of Information Science in Gathering Biodiversity and Neuroscience Data"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303164747/http://www.asis.org/Bulletin/Oct-03/levincragin.html |date=2009-03-03 }}, Geoffrey A. Levin and Melissa H. Cragin, ''[[American Society for Information Science and Technology|ASIST]] Bulletin'', Vol. 30, No. 1, Oct. 2003</ref>
eBird is an example of [[crowdsourcing]],<ref>nytcrowdsource {{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/science/earth/crowdsourcing-for-the-birds.html?_r=0|title= Crowdsourcing, for the Birds|last= Robbins|first= Jim|date= 19 Aug 2013|publisher= New York Times|accessdate= 11 Dec 2013|deadurl= no|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140418041104/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/science/earth/crowdsourcing-for-the-birds.html?_r=0|archivedate= 2014-04-18|df= }}</ref> and has been hailed as an example of [[democratizing science]], treating [[Citizen science|citizens as scientists]], allowing the public to access and use their own data and the collective data generated by others.<ref>[http://www.ecologyandsociety.org/vol13/iss2/resp1/ "Science Explicitly for Nonscientists"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108042444/http://www.ecologyandsociety.org/vol13/iss2/resp1/ |date=2009-01-08 }}, Caren B. Cooper, Janis L. Dickinson, Tina Phillips, Rick Bonney, ''[[Ecology and Society]]'', Vol. 13, No. 2, r1, 2008</ref>
==History and purpose== Launched in 2002 by the [[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] at [[Cornell University]] and the [[National Audubon Society]], eBird gathers basic data on bird abundance and distribution at a variety of spatial and temporal scales. It was mainly inspired by the ÉPOQ database, created by Jacques Larivée in 1975. As of November 2016, over 330,000 unique users have submitted over 100 million checklists,<ref>https://www.cope.es/noticias/biodiversidad/espana-encabeza-lista-europea-registros-observaciones-aves_240778</ref> from more than 250 countries and data for over 10,300 species to the program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://help.ebird.org/customer/portal/questions/1325149-how-many-people-ebird-around-the-world-and-per-country-|title=How many people eBird around the world and per country |website=ebird.org |accessdate=28 April 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201021306/http://help.ebird.org/customer/portal/questions/1325149-how-many-people-ebird-around-the-world-and-per-country-|archivedate=1 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ebird.org/content/ebird/news/ebird-top100-goes-global/|title=eBird Top100 goes global! - eBird|first=Team|last=eBird|date=|website=ebird.org|accessdate=28 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201021423/http://ebird.org/content/ebird/news/ebird-top100-goes-global/|archivedate=1 December 2016|df=}}</ref> As of June 2018 there are now now over 500 million bird observations recorded through this global database.<ref>http://smdp.com/saving-the-earth-with-artificial-intelligence-ai/167047</ref> In recent years there have been over 100 million bird observations recorded each year.<ref>https://ebird.org/about</ref>
eBird’s goal is to maximize the utility and accessibility of the vast numbers of bird observations made each year by recreational and professional [[bird watchers]]. The observations of each participant join those of others in an international network.<ref>http://smdp.com/saving-the-earth-with-artificial-intelligence-ai/167047</ref> Due to the variability in the observations the volunteers make, AI filters observations through collected historical data to improve accuracy.<ref>http://smdp.com/saving-the-earth-with-artificial-intelligence-ai/167047</ref> The data are then available via internet queries in a variety of formats.
===Use of Database Information===
The eBird Database has been used by scientists to determine the connection between bird migrations and [[monsoon]] rains in [[India]] validating traditional knowledge.<ref>https://www.indiatimes.com/technology/news/how-pied-cuckoos-signal-monsoon-rains-in-india-tech-that-demystifies-its-ancient-folklore-347733.html</ref> It has also been used to notice bird distribution changes due to [[climate change]] and help to define migration routes.<ref>https://www.cope.es/noticias/biodiversidad/espana-encabeza-lista-europea-registros-observaciones-aves_240778</ref> A study conducted found that eBird lists were accurate at determining population trends and distribution if there were 10,000 checklists for a given area.<ref>https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/03/180312085117.htm</ref>
==Features== eBird documents the presence or absence of species, as well as bird abundance through checklist data. A web interface allows participants to submit their observations or view results via interactive queries of the database. Internet tools maintain personal bird records and enable users to visualize data with interactive maps, graphs, and bar charts. All these features are available in 27 languages, including: [[Bulgarian (language)|Bulgarian]], [[Chinese (language)|Chinese]] (Both Traditional and Simplified), [[Croatian (language)|Croatian]], [[Czech (language)|Czech]], [[Danish (language)|Danish]], [[Dutch (language)|Dutch]], [[German (language)|German]], [[English (language)|English]] (A variety of 11 English dialects), [[Faroese (language)|Faroese]], [[Finnish (language)|Finnish]], [[French (language)|French]] (4 French dialects), [[Creole (language)|Creole]], [[Hebrew (language)|Hebrew]], [[Indonesian (language)|Indonesian]], [[Icelandic (language)|Icelandic]], [[Italian (language)|Italian]], [[Japanese (language)|Japanese]], [[Latvian (language)|Latvian]], [[Malayalam (language)|Malayalam]], [[Mongolian (language)|Mongolian]], [[Bokmål|Norwegian (Bokmål)]], [[Polish (language)|Polish]], [[Portuguese (language)|Portuguese]] (Both Portugal and Brazilian Portuguese), [[Russian (language)|Russian]], [[Serbian (language)|Serbian]], [[Spanish (language)|Spanish]] (10 Spanish dialects), [[Swedish (language)|Swedish]], [[Thai (language)|Thai]], [[Turkish (language)|Turkish]], and [[Ukrainian (language)|Ukrainian]].<ref>https://help.ebird.org/customer/portal/articles/1596582-common-name-translations-in-ebird</ref>
It is a free service. Data are stored in a secure facility and archived daily, and is accessible to anyone via the eBird web site and other applications developed by the global [[biodiversity information]] community. For example, eBird data are part of the [[Avian Knowledge Network]] (AKN)[https://archive.is/20130221075928/http://www.avianknowledge.net/content], which integrates observational data on bird populations across the western hemisphere and is a data source for the digital ornithological reference [[Birds of North America]]. In turn, the AKN feeds eBird data to international biodiversity data systems, such as the [[Global Biodiversity Information Facility]].
===Electronic kiosks=== In addition to accepting records submitted from users' personal computers and mobile devices, eBird has placed [[Interactive kiosk|electronic kiosks]] in prime birding locations, including one in the education center at the [[J. N. "Ding" Darling National Wildlife Refuge]] on [[Sanibel Island]] in [[Florida]].<ref>[http://www.cape-coral-daily-breeze.com/page/content.detail/id/503928.html?nav=5006 "eBirding, citizen science topic of ‘Ding’ presentation"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708114643/http://www.cape-coral-daily-breeze.com/page/content.detail/id/503928.html?nav=5006 |date=2011-07-08 }}, [[Cape Coral Daily Breeze]] Community News, Mar. 9, 2009</ref>
===Integration in Cars=== eBird is a part of Starlink on the new 2019 [[Subaru]] [[Subaru Ascent|Ascent]]. It allows eBird to be integrated into the touch screen of the car.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/dougnewcomb/2018/07/30/four-stand-out-tech-features-of-the-2019-subaru-ascent-limited/#224299e67225</ref>
